07531nam a22014655i 9780691184005DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911840057 a10.1515/97806911840052doi  a(DE-B1597)501829  a(OCoLC)1050437364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0150002bisacsh04a324.27309752231 aCaughey, Devin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Unsolid South :bMass Politics and National Representation in a One-Party Enclave /cDevin Caughey. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b20 b/w illus., 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in American Politics: Historical, International, and Comparative Perspectives ;v16500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The One-Party South: An Analytic Framework -- t3. Public Opinion in South and Nation -- t4. Southern Democrats in Congress -- t5. Democratic Primaries and the Selectoral Connection -- t6. Representation in the One-Party South -- t7. Conclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the Jim Crow era, the Democratic Party dominated the American South, presiding over a racially segregated society while also playing an outsized role in national politics. In this compelling book, Devin Caughey provides an entirely new understanding of electoral competition and national representation in this exclusionary one-party enclave. Challenging the notion that the Democratic Party's political monopoly inhibited competition and served only the Southern elite, he demonstrates how Democratic primaries-even as they excluded African Americans-provided forums for ordinary whites to press their interests.Focusing on politics during and after the New Deal, Caughey shows that congressional primary elections effectively substituted for partisan competition, in part because the spillover from national party conflict helped compensate for the informational deficits of elections without party labels. Caughey draws on a broad range of historical and quantitative evidence, including archival materials, primary election returns, congressional voting records, and hundreds of early public opinion polls that illuminate ideological patterns in the Southern public. Defying the received wisdom, this evidence reveals that members of Congress from the one-party South were no less responsive to their electorates than members from states with true partisan competition.Reinterpreting a critical period in American history, The Unsolid South reshapes our understanding of the role of parties in democratic theory and sheds critical new light on electoral politics in authoritarian regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyzSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical partieszSouthern StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aAmerican South.  aAmerican history.  aAmerican political development.  aDemocratic Party.  aDemocratic primaries.  aGreat Depression.  aJim Crow South.  aJim Crow era.  aNew Deal liberalism.  aNew Deal.  aSouthern Democrats.  aSouthern MCs.  aSouthern conservatism.  aSouthern politics.  aSouthern public.  aSouthern representatives.  aSouthern senators.  aU.S. Congress.  aaccountability.  aauthoritarian regimes.  acongressional politics.  acongressional representation.  acongressional responsiveness.  ademocracy.  ademocratic politics.  ademocratic regimes.  ademocratic theory.  aelectoral democracy.  aelectoral participation.  aelectoral politics.  aideo